{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"21251bc2-c489-48fc-a83e-7f44e4c16242","content":"With MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9, you can use **constructor injection** for `TestContext` and implement `IAsyncInitialization` for async setup:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization\n{\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    // Synchronous initialization via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        // sync setup work here\n    }\n\n    // Asynchronous initialization\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // async setup work here\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void MyTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor** — receives `TestContext` via DI; use for synchronous setup.\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`** — implement `InitializeAsync()` for async setup (runs after the constructor, before each test).\n- This replaces the older `[TestInitialize]` / `[ClassInitialize]` attribute pattern while still being supported alongside them.\n- `[AssemblyInitialize]` and `[ClassInitialize]` static methods are still used for one-time setup if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"89349b9e-591d-4ad9-8ecd-329c85869878","outputTokens":313,"requestId":"5803:3DF1E0:16EFD2F:186634E:6A0338AA"},"id":"e879775b-aabb-4438-9c7e-048a7fd56bbc","timestamp":"2026-05-12T14:26:58.734Z","parentId":"dd1a8b14-d683-4a07-b601-7619cb533d31"}
